Enchanters please stop the madness...please! I too am tired of hearing the &quot;Any Enchanter can easily perma-charm a mob that is better than what DC gives you.&quot; Why is it that in the zones I've been in where there are plenty of mobs of level 49 to 55 for the picking don't I see every enchanter doing this. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Right around Kunark everyone made one of two classes, either an enchanter or an iksar monk.  There are now hundreds of them running around pretending to be enchanters or monks.  Some of them actually learned to play the class most didn't.  Want to come play on CT some time, you and I can sit in Seb all day and I will charm mobs to your hearts little content.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Originally posted by Soulcraver</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
You always have to have some kind of Mez memmed for overpulls which you may have to use on your charm broken pet, because you have to do CC work and don't have the time to re-charm and CC at the same time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
My break down of spells in an exp group is charm, color slant, color skew, tash, theft of though, slow, dazzle, aoe mez.  You get an over pull and charm breaks, stun, aoe mez, charm, problem solved.  Crowd control is a joke, most groups don’t even bother with it anymore just killing everything.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Originally posted by Soulcarver</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
The mana use alone is high. Boltrans a mob (assume it sticks), mob breaks charm after 20 sec instead of the MAX 8 min. Mob starts beating snot out of you. You cast stun (no effect)--you're now down 2 bubs of health.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If the first stun is resisted you cast the second stun, if that is resisted you just dump AOE mez.  By the time you run through all of that the first stun is back up.  Mana use is totally irrelevant to me.  TOT is every 2 minutes and there are always plenty of casters around.  Speaking of casters if you charm shamans and wizards, guess what they open with a spell 99.9% of the time when they break.  Casting time on Boltrans is faster then whatever level 9 spell they decide to cast on me.  So by picking the correct mob to charm you can eliminate the need to even stun 90% of the time.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Originally posted by Soulcarver</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Questions, how much more mana did you use? how much more risk did you personally take? How much longer did you prolong the fight? How much more risk did you add to the party? The answer is more for each of those if you are honest.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The answer may be more but does that make it the right answer.  To quote an often used phrase it boils down to risk versus reward.  In your example we are fighting multiple mobs, what about the risk to the party bringing multiple mobs into camp.  Wouldn't it have been better to only bring one mob in the first place?  Everything is with risk, that is part of the game.  The question is what is an acceptable risk and what is just being reckless.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Originally posted by Soulcarver</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Even under PERFECT circumstances where boltrans NEVER broke you would expend approximately 3000 mana in charms in an hour--a full mana bar. One, nothing is perfect so the number is probably double that. How do have the mana to expend and buff the party and slow the mobs.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Lets double that number and say in one hour I spent 6000 mana charming.  Lets say that every four minutes I cast theft of thought, hmm that equals 6000 mana back.  Never mind the fact that I would obviously have C2/GOB or C3 up plus some med time here and there.  Charm being alteration which 99.9% of enchanters take as their spec line but we will just forget about that as well.  Rarely if ever do I slow mobs because for the most part people's AC far exceeds the mobs attack so damage is minimal, and it limits the effectiveness of druid/mage damage shields.  I usually find out where the cleric is at mana wise and toss slows based on his mana needs.  With CH and the levels of gear out there now, slow is more a hindrance in many situations then a help.  Given my epic (which as pointed out every guild makes an effort to get for an enchanter unlike a mages epic) haste is free so that leaves C3 which lasts 2.5hrs and maybe GRM.  Enchanters generally <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> never</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> run out of mana.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Originally posted by Soulcarver</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
And because of all this, do you take the risk to Epic haste your HIGHER level pet just incase it decides to grow unfriendly?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Absolutely.  Plus I would give him two weapons to quad.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Originally posted by Soulcarver</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Therefore, given the risk/reward and mana expenditure the vast majority of enchanters choose not to go this root. Which, BTW, was the intent of the spell. High risk POTENTIAL high return.[/b]<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The high risk potential is your assessment, other then having you come watch myself charm mobs all day there is little I can do to dissuade you from that belief.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Originally posted by Soulcarver</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Conclusion, DC decreases risk substantially and increases reward substantially in ALL situations it can be used. And there are LOTS of situations in which it can be used.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well good job stating the obvious, I don't think anyone has disputed that.  In places like Chardok, Howling Stone, Sebilis, etc. dire charm is now obviously the preferred choice.  The point is that if it goes away its impact to enchanters will be barely noticeable.  You overstate the usefulness and my guess is you have never actually been in a group with somebody who has the skill, why because any enchanter who knows better is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.telusplanet.net/public/olding/aoe.txt">doing this</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
