 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulumine.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lumine</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#333333>(2/5/02 11:28:49 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=67.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dire Charm (a poll, not flame/rant)</span><hr size=1> Hi all.  I haven't checked in on this thread in a few days, now I wish I had.  Many good thoughts here  - thanks for letting a chanter pop in and thanks for the lack of flamage.<br>
<br>
First off, let me add to what I was saying about charming higher level mobs.  If it sounded like I was trying to say that it was risk free then I misspoke.  Charming high level mobs is something you do only in certain places and only with certain mobs.  Last night in The Grey I had good success with Timeless Golems because they're naturally slow moving, have a low aggro range, low MR, they have a ton of HP's, and (hasted) they can take out any other mob in the zone.  Had I tried the same thing in the same zone with Rockfiends I would have died, no question about it.  Hell, I went one zone over and tried to charm a light blue Rockhopper (for fun) and nearly died when I got resisted twice.  <br>
<br>
Charm soloing is not a sure thing, by any means, and those people who pointed out that chanters have to be well prepared and extremely careful when doing it are exactly right.  And yes, the idea of having a DC pet is a comfort, but there's a risk/reward involved.  The exp/time that I can get with a level 53 pet is significantly higher than what I can get with a 46.<br>
<br>
Merauk has addressed the mechanics of charming in groups very well, so I'll let that stand.  In 90% of the situations where I'm using a pet for exp I'll have loaded the same spells that I always have loaded for exp groups anyway:  slow, theft, root, two stuns, single and ae mez.  That leaves a swap slots for tash, dot, haste, crack, etc.  Note that charming a shammie mob makes for a net zero change in my spell slots.  I load my charm spell in the slot that the slow spell was using, the slows now being handled by my pet.<br>
<br>
Why don't you see more chanters charming in places like Sebilis?  Simple - most chanters are content to sit on their asses and buff.  Why take risks?  There's often two tanks and usually two healers taking care of them, what's the point of charming?  Exp comes easy enough, and hell, I'm just going to be back here tomorrow night doing the same thing .. what's the hurry?  These are the chanters who will try charming a few times, see how much work it is, and never try again.  Will these people be doing DC?  Prolly not - they just have a chanter so they can camp dungeon loot for their alts.<br>
<br>
Chanters who DO charm know that you can add 50% to the damage output of the entire group (more or less) by accepting some risk.  If there's mobs to be pulled, I charm and keep the charm until there's nothing left to pull.  Then, MAYBE, we barbecue the pet.<br>
<br>
For the folks who thought I was lying when I said that crowd control was not the defining role for enchanters, I should say that I was thinking of those chanters for whom DC was an option.  The sad truth is that after level 55 or so, most chanters get demoted to buff machines.  Pullers at that level are generally very good at splitting and chanters just don't have much to do (another reason to put you chanter in charge of a charmed pet).  Do I still keep all my CC spells loaded?  Of course.  Do I get to use them?  Usually just on charm breaks. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Finally, I really don't think mages need to worry about their place in the universe after DC.  Think about it - what does a DC pet really replace?  The mage, who can use all my mana buffs, who can nuke and DS, who can generally take care of himself and his pet?  Not from my point of view.  Anyone who brings the sort of damage that mages bring without a healer load is just what I want for my group.  <br>
<br>
No, the people who need to worry are the tanks.  <br>
<br>
A chanter, a wizzy, and a mage walk into a zone, grab an 8000 HP mob, and proceed to own.  No, no healer needed, thanks.  If this one dies we'll just grab another.<br>
<br>
